%S A393940 12,18,20,28,32,44,45,50,52,63,68,75,76,92,98,99,116,117,124,147,148,
%T A393940 153,164,171,172,175,188,207,212,236,242,243,244,245,261,268,275,279,
%U A393940 284,292,316,325,332,333,338,356,363,369,387,388,404,412,423,425,428
%N A393940 Numbers m such that tau(m) is a perfect number (A000396).
%C A393940 Sequence deviates from A030515 and A162947, the smallest term that is not term of these sequences is 960.
%C A393940 Conjecture: number m = 18 is only number such that tau(m) and phi(m) are both perfect numbers.
%C A393940 This is the sequence of the smallest numbers m such that tau(m) = A000396(n): 12, 960, 1014686023680 = A081620(31), A081620(127), ...
%C A393940 Conjecture is false: with m = 2^61 * 17 * 65537 * ((2^2281-1)*2^2200+1), tau(m) and phi(m) are both perfect numbers. - _Michel Marcus_, Mar 12 2026
%H A393940 Michel Marcus, <a href="/A393940/b393940.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A393940 factordb, <a href="https://factordb.com/index.php?id=1100000000764174646">(2^2281-1)*2^2200+1</a>.
%e A393940 Number 12 is in the sequence because tau(12) = 6 (perfect number).
%t A393940 Select[Range[500], DivisorSigma[-1, DivisorSigma[0, #]] == 2 &] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 03 2026 *)
%o A393940 (Magma) [m: m in [1..500] | &+Divisors(#Divisors(m)) eq 2 * #Divisors(m)];
%o A393940 (PARI) isok(m) = my(d=numdiv(m)); sigma(d) == 2*d; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Mar 12 2026
%Y A393940 Cf. A146542 (sigma(m) is a perfect number), A393942 (phi(m) is a perfect number).
%Y A393940 Cf. A000005 (tau), A000010 (phi), A000396, A020488, A081357 (sublime numbers).
%Y A393940 Cf. A030515 (subsequence), A137491 (subsequence).
%K A393940 nonn,changed
%O A393940 1,1
%A A393940 _Jaroslav Krizek_, Mar 03 2026
